Issues.Body:
This is about **Bulma**.

This seems to be a bug but I might be doing it wrong as well. I was trying to modify bulma using node-sass and while I was able to modify the background color by setting a new value for `$body-background-color` variable, nothing seemed to work when I tried to modify the font color by setting a new value for the `$body-color` variable. The font family also didn't change.

I'm using Bulma **version** 0.7.5
<!-- My **browser** is: Google Chrome v77.0.3865.90

### Steps to reproduce

1. Follow https://bulma.io/documentation/customize/with-node-sass/ to set everything up.
2. Set a new value for `$body-background-color` to `#363636` and `$body-color` to `#dedede`

### Expected behavior

I expected it to change the color of background to dark grey and color to light grey.

### Actual behavior

It changed the background color to dark grey but the font color remained same thus making the text disappear because of the color similarities.

Here's my scss file
```
@charset "utf-8";
@import "https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Montserrat:400,700&display=swap";

$grey-dark: #363636;
$font-color: hsl(0%, 0%, 86%);

$body-family: "Monsterrat", sans-serif;
$body-background-color: $grey-dark;
$body-color: #FFFFFF;

@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/utilities/_all.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/base/_all.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/elements/button.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/elements/container.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/elements/title.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/components/navbar.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/layout/hero.sass";
@import "../node_modules/bulma/sass/layout/section.sass";
```

This is about **Bulma**.
This is about the **Bulma CSS framework**
I'm using Bulma **0.7.5**
Feature Request/Help

### Overview of the problem
I've checked the tag.scss to see if I could find something similar to what I wanted to do, but I didn't find. I also saw this issue #959 and saw it was closed, but I am not sure if i did not understand the solution `You can use the buttons class for that`, but replacing the whole tag to button does not give me the same result.

I wanted to use `is-outlined` helper the same way we can with buttons on tags! 
I did an workaround for that: i copied the same logic of `is-outlined` from buttons to tag.

```
.tag {
  @each $name, $pair in $colors {
    $color: nth($pair, 1);
    $color-invert: nth($pair, 2);

    &.is-#{$name} {
      &.is-outlined {
        background-color: transparent;
        border-style: solid;
        border-width: 1px;
        border-color: $color;
        color: $color;

        &:hover,
        &.is-hovered,
        &:focus,
        &.is-focused {
          background-color: $color;
          border-color: $color;
          color: $color-invert;
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

### Steps to Reproduce
`<span class="tag is-outlined">`

edit:
I managed to make it a bit simpler, by doing this:
```
.tag.is-primary.is-outlined {
  @extend .button.is-primary.is-outlined;
  border: 1px solid;
}
```
I just don't get why this is not already included as feature out of the box :)
